Various problems

**Limit input**

Use a width limit modifier and do not pass the address of the array.  Pass the array (no `&amp;`) and that will convert to the address of the first element of the array.  Leading `&quot; &quot;` not needed in the format as `&quot;%s&quot;` tosses optional leading white-space already.


    int x = 10;
    char password[x];
    // scanf(&quot; %s&quot;, &amp;password);
    scanf(&quot;%9s&quot;, password);

Little reason to be stingy in buffer size.  Suggest:

    char password[80];
    scanf(&quot;%79s&quot;, password);


**Iterate to the null character**

    // Bad! this iterates 11 times!
    // for (x = 0; x &lt;= 10; x++)

    // Iterate up to the null character
    for (x = 0; password[x]; x++)

**Advanced: `is...()`**

`is...(int ch)` is valid for values in the `unsigned char` range and `EOF`.  Insure other negative values are not passed.

    // if (isupper(password[x]))
    if (isupper((unsigned char) password[x]))

---

Might as well use one loop.

    for (x = 0; password[x]; x++) {
      if (isdigit((unsigned char) password[x])) {
        number++;
      } else if (isupper((unsigned char) password[x])) {
        uppercase++;
      } else if (password[x] == &#39;$&#39;) {
        dollar++;
      }
    }

---

**Advanced: security**

Good to scrub memory when done with passwords.  

    volatile char *p = password; 
    for (x = 0; x &lt; sizeof password; x++)
      p[x] = 0;
    }

Note: `memset(password ...)` is no good as it may be optimize out.

